<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Given television's supposed power, it is astonishing how little it is used
to publicise wrongs and, with luck, help to right them. Some series do have
a tradition of investigation ('World In Action', for instance) but that is
most unusual. All the more reason, then, to celebrate the role of Taking
Liberties which highlights miscarriages of social justice. Today's programme
(8.00 BBC2) takes up the case of the Moroccans who were persuaded to work in
Gibraltar when Spain closed the border in 1969 but, now that the political
situation has changed, are facing deportation. Equally rare are programmes
in which a single powerful opinion can be expressed without an opposing view
being used for 'balance'. Opinions on C4 (8.00) provides half an hour for
the expression of a single belief. Today Bob Tyrell, managing director of
the Henley Centre, predicts the weakening of group attitudes as the 'me
generation' of the Sixties ages. This Week investigates terrorist killing in
Northern Ireland but, for once, looks not at the IRA but at the Protestant
UDA which, since vowing a year ago to avenge every killing by the IRA, has
done just that (8.30 ITV).
</TEXT>
