<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 92 / Estate agents' image improved, Borrie says
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE RECESSION and tighter regulations governing estate agents are combining
to improve the image of the profession, Sir Gordon Borrie, director-general
of fair trading, said yesterday.
Complaints were still being made, he said, but the image of estate agents
had improved, he told the annual conference of the National Association of
Estate Agents in London.
'A short time ago, the image of estate agents could hardly have been worse,'
Sir Gordon said.
'Any stand-up comedian searching for an easy laugh could . . . (conjure) up
a picture of a wide boy with a cellular phone making a fortune out of other
peoples' homes with very little effort.'
But the recession meant 'a number of people' had left the estate agency
business.
'When you add to that the greater requirements of the new regulations, the
image of the estate agent has improved. I see no reason why it should not
improve.'
The Office of Fair Trading had banned about 155 estate agents from the
property business in the past 10 years, and recently the rate of expulsions
had increased.
There was also a rise in complaints about estate agents.
'There is a greater awareness among the public that there are complaints
procedures and things can be done,' Sir Gordon said.
Mr David Ware, association chairman, said there should be a compulsory
registration scheme for estate agents to stop people with no qualifications
opening property offices.
It would be impractical to require every agent to have a licence but at
least one person should hold such a qualification in every estate agency
office, he said, adding that an upturn in the market was likely to mean
'cowboy' agents making a comeback.
Against that, Sir Gordon said a licensing system might lead to less choice
for consumers and increase the cost of selling a home.
</TEXT>
