FT  30 APR 92 / Nurses concerned at role of pay body
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DIFFERENCES emerged yesterday between the Royal College of Nursing and the
government over how National Health Service trusts should interpret
recommendations from the independent nurses' pay review body.
Mr Phil Gray, RCN director of labour relations, told reporters at the annual
congress in Blackpool trusts should use nationally recommended pay levels as
a baseline on which they could improve if they wished.
The Department of Health believes trusts should use national rates as a
'benchmark', or rough guide.
Trusts in theory are able to offer lower rates at the local level.
Earlier this week, Mrs Virginia Bottomley, the Health Secretary, addressing
the congress, refused to bind NHS trusts to observe pay levels set by the
pay review body.
It would be kept as a benchmark but trusts 'must be free to fix their own
rates,' she said.
No trust has yet offered rates of pay lower than those set by the review
body. The vast majority have this year stayed with nationally recommended
rates, although some have varied national terms and conditions of
employment.
Some 90 per cent of nurses are still covered by the terms of the pay review
body, because staff who have transferred from local health authority control
to trusts can retain their terms and conditions of employment.
Mr Gray warned of chaos if there were wide variations of pay in a locality.
</TEXT>
