<TEXT>
THE CREDENTIALS of Mr John Smith as the leadership candidate of Labour's
establishment were underlined yesterday with the publication of the list of
MPs making nominations for the election.
All but three of his shadow cabinet colleagues were among the 162 MPs who
nominated him. He also captured most of the new MPs and almost the entire
Scottish party, including its hard left.
His rival Mr Bryan Gould counted only two shadow cabinet leftwingers - Mr
Michael Meacher and Ms Jo Richardson - among his 63 supporters, as well as
his shadow environment colleagues and campaign managers, Mr David Blunkett
and Mr Clive Soley.
His other prominent supporters included the prominent Euro-sceptic and
former senior Cabinet minister, Mr Peter Shore, and Ms Clare Short from the
national executive committee.
Mr Robin Cook, shadow health secretary and Mr Smith's campaign manager, said
some 15 other MPs had indicated that they would support Mr Smith after
consulting their constituency parties.
Mr Ken Livingstone, the candidate of the left-wing Campaign group, captured
only half the faction's membership.
In the deputy leadership race, the bulk of the front bench formed the core
of Mrs Margaret Beckett's 89-strong support. Mr John Prescott, the third
challenger for deputy, won many of his 64 nominations from leftwing northern
and Scottish MPs.
The annual conference of the AEU engineering union, the third-largest union
affiliated to Labour, yesterday backed Mr John Smith and Mrs Margaret
Beckett as leader and deputy leader of the party. The AEU decided not to
ballot its members.
