<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The younger comedians in the wake of the generation which seems to be
rapidly passing away (Eric Morecambe, Tommy Cooper, Frankie Howerd, Benny
Hill) appear to be obsessed by boredom. Paul Morley begins a new run of his
half-hour series The Thing Is .. with 'Boredom' (8.30 C4). He talks about
boredom to Claire Rayner (there is a programme somewhere this week without
Claire Rayner in it), Peter Cook, and Thora Hird. Then we are told that in
Sean's Show Sean Hughes' best friend writes a book 'exposing Sean's
incredibly boring life' (10.30 C4). Could it be that these young men suspect
that, compared to their predecessors, they really are boring? Could they be
right? BBC2's series The Buried Mirror about 'Spain and the new world',
written and presented by Carlos Fuentes, began with a competent, uninspiring
history of Spain. Today's episode compares Aztec customs and religion with
the Christian variety of the Conquistadores. The BBC describes Mr
Wakefield's Crusade as 'darkly comic'. Others might call it obscurely weird.
Peter Capaldi plays the rich amateur sleuth (9.40 BBC2).
</TEXT>
