<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 92 / GrandMet sells Express Foods' Irish dairy interest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GUY DE JONQUIERES and TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GRAND Metropolitan, the UK food and drinks group, yesterday took a further
step in the disposal of its Express dairy and foods business with an
agreement to sell Express Foods' Irish dairy interests in a series of deals
worth IPounds 99m (Pounds 90m).
The Express operations in the Republic of Ireland and Northern Ireland,
except for an 80 per cent interest in Carbery Milk Products, are to be sold
to Waterford Foods for IPounds 63m.
In addition, GrandMet will retain ownership of Express Foods Group
(Ireland).
The assets of Express Foods Group (Ireland) will consist of IPounds 15m in
cash and receivables after the deal is completed.
The Express stake in Carbery Milk Products, a Cork-based cheesemaker, is to
be sold for IPounds 21m to Carbery Creameries, a co-operative of dairy
farmers which supply the business with liquid milk.
The businesses being acquired from GrandMet by Waterford are Virginia Milk
Products, Express Northern Foods and WED, an Express Dairies joint venture
with Waterford Co-op.
The deal will make Waterford the leading dairy group in Ireland, with
projected annual sales of IPounds 700m and control over about a fifth of
Ireland's liquid milk output. At present, Waterford has 29 per cent of the
liquid milk market nationally and 72 per cent in Dublin.
Waterford has spent IPounds 215m on acquisitions in the UK, the US and
Ireland since it was floated on the stock market in 1988. It has 25 per cent
of the liquid milk market in the north-west of Britain, 15 per cent of the
UK fruit juice market and 45 per cent of the US condensed milk market.
Yesterday's deals, which are subject to Irish regulatory approval, provide
for Waterford to continue supplying GrandMet with cream for its Bailey's
Original Irish Cream liqueur.
In November, GrandMet sold its Express Dairy and Eden Vale businesses to
Northern Foods for Pounds 359m. The only Express businesses remaining with
GrandMet are the UK cheese and food service operations.
GrandMet decided to sell the Express operations because they do not fit with
its current strategy of focusing on international branded businesses.
Acquisitive Waterford, Page 28
</TEXT>
