<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 92 / Volkswagen chief seeks change in employer attitudes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DRASTIC CHANGES will be required in long-standing attitudes governing
industrial relations if European economies are to prosper, Dr Carl Hahn,
chairman of Volkswagen, told the conference.
Dr Hahn, whose company this week faces the prospect of strikes, said the
Marxist concept of a fundamental gulf between labour and capital had been
consigned to 'the dustbin of history'. But employers had yet to dismantle
the old demarcations and divisions which still characterised the workforce.
He said the internal world of the company could no longer be one of
'upstairs and downstairs'. In all divisions and at all levels of corporate
life, entirely new attitudes and qualifications were needed if businesses
were to meet successfully the increasingly complex challenges confronting
them.
Employers, Dr Hahn stressed, had to create a climate in their companies
which permitted all staff to contribute to the success of the business.
The best solution to harmonious progress was to bring all workers closer to
the creation and management of resources and to imbue them with a sense of
ownership through increased participation and responsibility.
Dr Hahn said the biggest challenge facing Europe was to spread capitalist
principles across the continent.
The liberated peoples of central and eastern Europe had to be given hope and
must not be allowed to begin to yearn for a return to the old days of
communism.
It was politically essential that examples demonstrating the benefits of the
western system were established in formerly communist central Europe without
delay.
It was 'the perfect place to build bridges, across which knowhow and capital
can flow still further eastwards'.
</TEXT>
