<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 92 / Tide of relief greets Major
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT HAD been a very close-run thing, Mr Peter Morgan, director-general of the
IoD, told the 2,500 people attending the institute's 43rd annual convention,
Michael Cassell writes.
They hardly needed reminding that their victory rally, following the Tories'
fourth consecutive election victory, could just as easily have been a wake.
The prospect of Mr John Smith with his hands deep in the pockets of the
well-paid and of his sidekick Mr Gordon Brown barging into boardrooms all
over the country had been very real when delegates were booking their Pounds
120-a-head places.
The IoD was well-prepared for the worst. If Labour had won, the smoked
salmon timbale in the famous luncheon hampers was unlikely to have been
replaced with a prawn cocktail. But Mr Neil Kinnock would certainly have
been asked to make yesterday's keynote speech.
His performance would have been unlikely to provoke the enraptured response
he won at his triumphalist Sheffield gathering a month ago.
'He would have been lucky to get back to his seat before the applause
stopped,' said Mr Jerry Hughes, a Black Country finance director.
In the event, Mr John Major emerged, almost sheepishly, from behind a black
curtain to reassure his audience that everything was really going to be all
right.
Mr Major, it seems, was invited to speak to the IoD when he became foreign
secretary but was moved on before he could keep the date. He was invited
again as chancellor but was once more moved. This time, he was still in the
job as prime minister and seemed to find the situation quite satisfactory.
So did his audience. Behind evident surprise and relief there was a warm
welcome for Mr Major's pledge to complete Mrs Thatcher's trade union reforms
and to keep a wary eye on Brussels.
There was, above all, widespread enthusiasm for the prospect of a period of
political stability and of an end to the recession. Recovery, the prime
minister said, had been waiting in the wings and a return of confidence
would now speed up the revival.
Few in the audience, however, were yet prepared to say the recession was
over. Sir Nigel Mobbs, chairman of Slough Estates, said most businessmen
would be encouraged by Mr Major's bullish appraisal of prospects for
economic recovery. 'We cannot expect it all to happen within weeks of an
election victory,' he said. 'But we have averted a national disaster.'
Few of the captains of industry would have disagreed.
</TEXT>
