<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 92 / Fall expected in lending to property groups
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BANK LENDING to property companies, which stands at a record Pounds 39.2bn,
will decline at a rate of Pounds 2bn a year for the next four years,
according to research by Savills, the firm of chartered surveyors.
This heavy debt burden is one of the severest problems facing the property
industry, which is suffering its biggest decline for 50 years.
In spite of a marginal decline from a peak of Pounds 40.7bn last May to
Pounds 39.2bn, property debt is, in real terms, more than three times what
it was in 1974  - the year of the last property crash. If construction
companies are included in the figures, property lending totals Pounds 55bn.
The UK property sector raised Pounds 3.9bn in new funds last year, a 4 per
cent decline on 1990.
Nearly half the new funds came from a record number of rights issues by
property companies, which raised Pounds 2.03bn. The remainder of the new
funds came from Pounds 1.5bn of loans and Pounds 450m through bonds. Most of
the new funds were used to refinance existing debts.
Leaving aside a total of Pounds 250m that was raised by housing
associations, just Pounds 780m was left as 'new' money for the industry.
Net institutional investment increased from Pounds 1.3bn to Pounds 2.2bn
last year, according to government statistics.
However, figures from the Investment Property Databank, an independent
research group, indicate a fall in net investment to just under Pounds 1bn
last year.
In the first quarter of this year very little new money was raised by the
property industry as a result of a weak stock market and the uncertainty
surrounding the general election.
The UK clearing banks will need to make provisions of Pounds 3.5bn to Pounds
4bn against their property loans, according to County NatWest, the merchant
banking arm of National Westminster Bank.
The clearing banks have a property exposure of Pounds 17.2bn.
County NatWest expects the banks to recognise the losses over a number of
years, during which time they will tend to support distressed companies.
County's chief concern is directed at the attitude of overseas lenders,
particularly as a result of the decline in the Japanese property and equity
markets.
Financing Property 1992. Savills, 20 Grosvenor Hill, Berkeley Square, London
W1X 0HQ. Free.
Property; An Essay on Finance. County NatWest, 135 Bishopsgate, London EC2M
3XT. Price on application.
