</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WESTMINSTER gave birth to a new think tank last night
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
the first to link a pro-EC stance with the market-led economic philosophy of
Thatcherism.
President of the European Policy Forum is Mr Graham Mather, who recently
quit after five years as director-general of the right-wing Institute of
Economic Affairs over political differences with the IEA's Euro-sceptic
founders.
The forum, chaired by Lord Hunt of Tanworth, a cabinet secretary to four
prime ministers, is described as 'a non-partisan combination of discussion
forum, channel for international contacts and think tank'.
Membership of its governing council crosses a wide range of political
territory. It includes Lord Alexander, chairman of National Westminster
Bank, Sir Christopher Tugendhat, former Tory EC commissioner, Lord Holme,
leading Liberal Democrat policy adviser, Sir Roy Denman, former EC
ambassador to Washington, Mr Goron Tunhammar, president of the Swedish
employers' federation, Mr Samuel Brittan, an assistant editor of the
Financial Times, and Mr Martin Jacques, former editor of Marxism Today.
Launching the forum at its Queen Anne's Gate offices last night, Lord Hunt
told an audience which included Mr John Major, the prime minister, that the
Maastricht treaty  - while a great achievement  - had prompted concern about
an overly centralist Community that raised new challenges. 'This does not
mean a retreat into Euro-scepticism, but rather finding the right way
forward,' he said.
He added that the forum had received non-partisan support, including
finance, from across Europe.
The forum was also welcomed by Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary. 'I
look forward eagerly to pungent and stimulating contributions to debate from
the European Policy Forum,' he said.
While the forum stresses the catholic nature of its support, it will focus
on deregulation and the transformation of public services.
Mr Frank Vibert is also joining from the IEA as a director.
