FT  29 APR 92 / Victorian work set for record: Saleroom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONE of the finest fairy paintings by the Victorian artist Richard Dadd,
Contradiction: Oberon and Titania, could fetch Pounds 1.5m when it is sold
at Christie's in London on June 12.
It was painted at the Bethlem Hospital in Southwark, where Dadd was
committed in 1844 after murdering his father in a fit of madness.
The oval picture, based on a scene from A Midsummer Night's Dream, sold at
auction in 1964 for Pounds 7,000. By 1983, with Victorian art in great
demand, it sold to an American collector for Pounds 550,000, a world record
at the time for a Victorian picture.
London is host this week to a series of Islamic sales.
This has been a difficult market in recent years but Christie's was pleased
with its total of Pounds 699,000, with 87 per cent sold, from yesterday
morning's auction. The top price was Pounds 60,500 for sections of a 13th
century North African Qur'an.
A late 15th century manuscript of love lyrics composed by Shah Mohammed
Nishapuri doubled its original estimate at Pounds 55,000.
Christie's in New York at the weekend secured a world auction record for an
illustrated book when it sold a copy of Audubon's The Birds of America for
Dollars 4m (Pounds 2.3m).
