<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 92 / TGWU is seen as 'personnel-heavy'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The TGWU, Britain's biggest union, is too 'expensive, bureaucratic and
personnel-heavy,' according to a report from Klein &amp; Co, management
consultants. They criticised the the 11 TGWU regions for acting as
'mini-unions'.
Their report said the union should introduce proper budgeting and accounting
systems and use resources more efficiently.
Mr Bill Morris, TGWU general secretary, outlined the main findings of the
report but stressed that no decisions had been taken on it. He indicated
that the three smallest regions  - on the north coast, south coast and east
coast  - were likely to be merged.
He was unclear about how the political and financial autonomy of the
remaining regions would be reduced to create the 'one union' culture
recommended by Klein, but said there were no plans to centralise the
collection of union dues.
The report said the union should merge district offices, introduce proper
budgeting and accounting systems, provide more professional support for
officials and use its assets more efficiently. Its use of property,
including its headquarters in London, should be improved to reduce the
proportion  - 95 per cent  - of income the union derives from membership
subscriptions.
Mr Morris conceded that one reason the TGWU had missed out on mergers with
smaller unions was because it had been too 'fractured'.
</TEXT>
