<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 92 / Judges consider abandoning their wigs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON and ROBERT RICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CEREMONIAL wigs may be going out of fashion after almost 300 years.
As commercial court judges yesterday debated a proposal from the Commercial
Bar Association that barristers and judges should no longer have to wear
wigs, the new speaker of the Commons, Miss Betty Boothroyd, took her seat
without wearing the traditional wig.
Barristers have complained that wigs are uncomfortable and old-fashioned,
and say they intimidate the public. The commercial judges reached no
conclusions yesterday, but recommended widening the debate to all judges of
the Queen's Bench Division.
Lord Taylor, the new lord chief justice, said yesterday the question of
abandoning wigs was a matter for the Judges' Council, and no decision could
be taken without extensive consultation. He has previously expressed the
opinion that wigs are unnecessary.
Wigs became fashionable in the 17th century under King Charles II and were
adopted by lawyers among others.
Wigs then were made of human hair  - the horsehair wig worn by most
barristers today was invented by Humphrey Ravenscroft in 1822. His company,
Ede and Ravenscroft, the ceremonial outfitters, is still the main supplier
of legal wigs in the UK, and exports to countries with British-inspired
legal systems.
Even if barristers do cast aside their wigs, Ede and Ravenscroft's main
business  - robes for academics, lawyers and the royal family  - shows no
signs of disappearing.
Abandonment of wigs has been proposed before without result, but this time a
relaxation of the rules in some courts seems likely.
LORD MACKAY, the lord chancellor, denied yesterday that he intends to step
down in the autumn after five years in the job, Robert Rice writes.
His department said Lord Mackay was disturbed by continuing press
speculation that he no longer wished to continue in office.
Rumours began circulating in Whitehall shortly before the election that the
lord chancellor would not continue in office for more than six months.
His department said he had been unable to deny the rumours at the time
because the election campaign was under way and parliamentary convention
prevented him from making any statement.
The lord chancellor recently proposed to reduce the normal retirement age
for judges from 75 to 70.  At 65, he could thus remain in office until 1997.
Lord Mackay succeeded the late Lord Havers as lord chancellor in 1987.
</TEXT>
