<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 92 / International Company News: Tenneco income advances to
Dollars 33m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TENNECO, the US conglomerate in the throes of a restructuring, yesterday
reported a Dollars 32m improvement in first-quarter net income. It also
announced the loss of 2,250 jobs in Europe with the closure of three plants
run by its troubled Case equipment subsidiary.
The Houston-based company reported net income of Dollars 33m, or 20 cents a
share, compared with Dollars 1m or a loss of 3 cents per share last year on
revenues flat at Dollars 3.3bn. Operating income rose from Dollars 113m to
Dollars 215m. The figures were a little ahead of most analysts' forecasts,
but the shares dipped Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 43 1/2 .
Mr Michael Walsh, the new president and chief executive, is pushing through
a plan to restore the company to what he calls 'respectable levels of
profitability' and sharply cut the debt on its balance sheet.
The results included improved operating performances by all Tenneco's
divisions, although Case, which makes agricultural and construction
equipment, still lost Dollars 77m. That figure compares with a loss of
Dollars 147m a year ago, when the subsidiary took a Dollars 32m charge for
job cuts.
Case, which has been hit by a downturn in its markets and excessive
inventory levels, announced as part of its restructuring the closure of its
plants in Carvin, France and Zaragoza, Spain.
It would no longer manufacture high capacity excavators made at Carvin and
would source its wheel loaders and hydraulic cylinders made at Zaragoza.
It said it had also sold selected assets of its Vibromax compaction
equipment business and would close its plant in Dusseldorf, Germany, later
this year.
These actions, which will reduce its European plants from 12 to nine, form
part of a previously announced two-year plan to cut Case's employment from
30,000 people at the end of 1990 to about 20,000 at the end of this year.
Mr Walsh said Case had met its performance targets for the quarter but
refused to be drawn on when it might return to profit or whether he might
sell the business.
Operating expenses were significantly lower, while the subsidiary's
worldwide production dropped 25 per cent from a year ago and dealer
inventories fell Dollars 900m.
</TEXT>
