FT  29 APR 92 / UK Company News: Plastiseal dives into red after poor second
half
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PLASTISEAL, which manufactures windows and doors, mainly for the public
sector, dipped sharply into the red last year following poor sales in the
second half.
The USM-traded company incurred a pre-tax deficit of Pounds 780,000 for the
12 months to January 31, struck after exceptional charges of Pounds 269,000
(Pounds 520,000), as profits of Pounds 496,000 on property disposals were
offset by closure and re-organisation costs of Pounds 765,000.
Properties worth a further Pounds 700,000 are being held for resale.
The outcome compared with profits of Pounds 310,000 last time and Pounds
438,000 at the interim stage. Turnover fell to Pounds 13.7m (Pounds 18m).
There was an operating loss of Pounds 147,000 (Pounds 1.15m profit).
Mr Anthony Marson, who took over as chairman this month, said that the
company was affected by lower local authority and Property Services Agency
spending.
However, he said that there has been a slight improvement since the election
and that the company is expected to return to profit this year.
Interest charges increased to Pounds 364,000 (Pounds 320,000) on net
borrowings of about Pounds 3.5m.
Year-end gearing went above 100 per cent, due to seasonal factors, but it
has since been reduced.
Mr Michael Price, one of the two former joint chairmen, has resigned. The
other, Mr Howard Manttan, becomes managing director.
The Nuneaton head office is being closed down while uPVC window
manufacturing has been transferred from Bury to Coventry.
Losses per share emerged at 6.2p (earnings 2.4p) and the final dividend is
passed, leaving a total of 1.5p.
