FT  29 APR 92 / Leading Lisbon business family suffers new blow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK BLUM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LISBON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE MURDER yesterday of Mr Joao Champalimaud, son of one of Portugal's most
prominent entrepreneurs, is the latest act in a drama that goes back to the
seizure of the family's business assets in 1975 when Portugal's revolution
took a sharp turn to the left.
Mr Champalimaud, 41, was shot and stabbed in his Lisbon office just before
9am. The killing is thought to be the consequence of a private grievance.
Before the revolution, the group headed by Mr Antonio Champalimaud, Joao's
father, controlled a bank, two large insurance companies, and many other
industrial assets.
Since then the family, operating from exile in Brazil where it owns a large
cement factory, has fought successive Portuguese governments for the return
of its assets and compensation. Mr Joao Champalimaud played a leading role
in the negotiations.
Two weeks ago the group won back control of Mundial Confianca, one of
Portugal's top three insurance companies which it formerly owned,when it was
privatised. Mr Champalimaud's father celebrated the group's return to
Portugal after 16 years, by warning that he would clean the company of the
vestiges of socialism and of all personnel 'appointed by socialism'.
</TEXT>
