<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 92 / International Company News: IBM holds talks with clone maker
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE and LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INTERNATIONAL Business Machines, the world's largest computer manufacturer,
is in talks with Northgate Computer Systems. The talks may lead to IBM
taking a stake in the small personal computer manufacturer and to IBM
offering Northgate's 'clone' computers as a lower price alternative to its
own PC products.
Although no firm agreement has yet been reached the talks appear to be the
latest move by IBM to bolster its shrinking share of the world PC market.
The move follows IBM's agreement to develop advanced PCs with Apple
Computers, its arch rival. IBM is seeking deals with 'clone' manufacturers,
whose low-priced copies of IBM's designs cost IBM much of its PC market
dominance.
Clones are functionally and sometimes physically almost indistinguishable
from IBM's own designs. But because clone makers have lower fixed costs and
are prepared to accept much slimmer profit margins, their products sell for
lower prices.
With PC prices declining precipitously, IBM is looking for ways to compete
directly with priced machines, while at the same time maintaining the
premium brand appeal of its own Personal Systems products. IBM sells a clone
in south-east Asia through a joint venture company formed last year with
Hong Leong Corporation of Singapore.
In Europe, IBM is expected to offer PC clones built by an Asian manufacturer
through a newly-formed subsidiary that will focus on the low end of the PC
market.
An investment by IBM in Northgate could represent an opportunity for IBM to
offer lower priced products in the US.
Northgate, based in Minnesota, manufactures a complete line of
high-performance, low-cost clones, including notebook computers, desktop
machines and tower configurations.
Northgate's sales grew from Dollars 32m in 1988 to Dollars 203m in 1990, but
its attempts to expand sales organisation led to losses of Dollars 6.9m in
1990.
Since then the company has retrenched, reporting sales of Dollars 167m and
profits of Dollars 2.7m in 1991.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 27
</PAGE>
