<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 92 / Chancellor warns of tight public expenditure round
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
IMPROVED growth prospects in the US and Germany mean that 'growth should
become fully established' in the UK this year, Mr Norman Lamont, the
chancellor, said yesterday.
But in his first press conference since the election, he warned that a
'tight public expenditure round' would be necessary this autumn, and the
government would have to keep 'a very wary eye on the fiscal position over
the medium term'.
Mr Lamont said a firm line on public spending would be needed because the
recession in the UK had lasted longer than expected, swelling the public
sector deficit to a forecast Pounds 28bn in the current financial year.
He told fellow finance ministers at yesterday's meeting in Washington of the
International Monetary Fund's policy-making interim committee that Britain's
underlying fiscal position was strong. The lurch into deficit was 'primarily
due to the effects of the automatic stabilisers', particularly on the
revenue side.
The chancellor said he expected Britain's fiscal position 'to improve very
considerably' as the UK economy recovered.
He defended his refusal to stimulate the economy 'whether through
devaluation, premature cuts in interest rates or fiscal expansion'. It would
have been 'wholly irresponsible' to engineer 'a boom which would inevitably
have been temporary and unsustainable'. Mr Lamont said he expected the end
of pre-election uncertainty and improved world economic conditions would
unleash pent-up consumer demand in Britain, helping recovery.
He was given some encouragement in his view by relatively upbeat assessments
of conditions in the US and Germany from Mr Nicholas Brady, the US Treasury
secretary, and Mr Theo Waigel, the German finance minister.
'We are seeing clear signs of economic recovery now in the United States,'
Mr Brady said.
In Sunday's meeting of ministers from the Group of Seven leading industrial
countries, Mr Waigel reported that gross domestic product in western Germany
increased by 1 per cent in the first quarter of this year compared with the
final three months of 1991. He forecast that growth in Germany as a whole
would be 'a good 2 per cent' this year.
However, Mr Brady was concerned that growth prospects were less favourable
for the US's industrialised trading partners. 'On an aggregate basis, the
major industrial countries are experiencing their third straight year of
inadequate growth,' he said.
Sub-standard growth not only hurt the inhabitants of the industrialised
countries, by cutting income and raising unemployment, but - looking to
developments in eastern Europe and the former Soviet Union - 'it also
seriously jeopardises what is probably a unique opportunity in our lifetimes
to build an integrated, prosperous global market economy', Mr Brady said.
He stressed that a primary objective of the US and the European members of
the G7 was to secure a commitment to faster growth through fiscal stimulus
and easier monetary policy in Japan.
But these calls were rebuffed by Mr Tsutomu Hata, the finance minister of
Japan, and Mr Yasushi Mieno, the bank of Japan's hardline governor.
In trying to achieve the goal of a global market economy, the industrialised
countries at this year's spring meetings of the IMF and the World Bank have
focused on the need for stricter fiscal policies. This is seen as the way of
securing lower interest rates and stronger world growth.
It emerged yesterday that Mr Lamont had led the questioning of Germany's
high fiscal deficits in Sunday's meeting of G7 finance ministers. The
ministers spent more than two hours arguing with Japan over the need to
incorporate into the communique a thinly veiled call for Japan to increase
public spending to increase demand.
