<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 92 / Why Monday to Friday off is not an easy life: Diane Summers
reads between the lines of the Post Office's short week deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOR at least one group of workers in British industry, the much-heralded
Leisure Age has finally arrived. Post Office maintenance engineers have
signed an historic deal that will enable them to enjoy a 22-hour working
week for a full week's money.
Naturally, the arrangement is not as idyllic for the workers as it might
initially sound. The 22 hours will be concentrated into the weekend,
starting at 3.30pm on Friday afternoon and ending at 7am on Monday morning.
The short hours will only be available for part of the year - probably April
to July - and will depend on the workloads rather than be guaranteed each
week.
Nevertheless, there must have been many employees in other sectors who read
of the deal yesterday and wondered when it would be their turn. If the price
of getting Monday to Friday off work is having to work two shifts of up to
12 hours over the weekend, then many would consider it worth paying.
So is the Post Office agreement the first glimmer of the dawn of the Leisure
Age? In the 1960s it was thought that labour-saving devices, the rapid
development of technology and medical advances prolonging life, would lead
to such an excess of leisure time that disposing of it would be the
question.
Employment continues to be unevenly distributed, with part of the population
suffering stress-related illnesses because of working too many hours, while
the unemployed endure the opposite situation. Unions have tended to
reinforce the pattern because of short-term fears that their members would
lose overtime payments.
According to government figures, more than 1m members of the 25m workforce
are 'double-jobbers' who hold down two jobs.
Surprisingly, even during the recession, substantial amounts of overtime
have continued to be worked: in February, seasonally adjusted figures showed
more than 10m hours of overtime being worked each week in manufacturing.
That compared with a peak of more than 16m hours in April 1979 and a low of
8.5m hours in March 1981 during the last recession. With the overtime,
British men continue to work longer hours than men anywhere else in the
European Community.
Some reductions have been made, principally after a campaign by engineering
unions that resulted in a cut from 39 hours to 37 hours for hundreds of
thousands of workers. A further push to a 35-hour week, common among
white-collar workers, is being delayed by unions until after the recession.
Rather than being driven by Leisure Age considerations, the Post Office deal
is an indication of quite another trend, according to Mr Alastair Hatchett
from Incomes Data Services, the pay and conditions research group. Employers
are, for reasons of economy, increasingly seeking to eliminate premium
payments for overtime and integrate unsocial hours working into the normal
working week.
There are a number of ways of doing so, including the move to annualised
hours which means employees contract to work a total number of hours over
the year, rather than on a week-by-week basis. That system is particularly
effective in allowing employers to deal with peaks and troughs in demand.
Manual workers at Hotpoint factories in north Wales work variable hours
depending on seasonal demand for domestic appliances.
The National Communications Union, which has negotiated the Post Office
22-hour deal, is only too aware of another way employers commonly cope with
those peaks and troughs - by hiring and firing staff in time with workloads.
The Post Office's own construction and maintenance operation now has to
tender for work with outside contractors. Many of those contractors will not
be burdened - as the Post Office itself has been - with having to pay
workers when there is little to do during the week, while also shelling out
for weekend overtime.
According to Mr Bill Fry, NCU president, the Post Office agreement is a
breakthrough that might provide an example of the way forward for unions and
employers in other sectors. 'We are endeavouring to protect people's jobs -
that's my retort when some members complain they could lose overtime,' he
says.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
