<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 92 / The new boys and girls settle in: Philip Stephens tries to
pick winners among the latest intake of MPs on their first day at
Westminster
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT was not hard to spot the new boys and girls as they milled around in the
lobby of the House of Commons at yesterday's opening of the new parliament.
Apart from fresh faces and brightly polished shoes, most of Westminster's
new MPs sported proudly the photographic security badges which older hands
have long since removed from their lapels.
'It's rather embarassing really, but I suppose they must be allowed to show
off for a week or so,' offered one long-serving Tory.
A colleague confessed that his grandchildren looked older than some of those
with whom he would now be sharing a place on the government backbenches.
Not all the newcomers displayed the awkwardness that comes with
unfamiliarity.
The more worldly-wise on the Conservative side were already busy arranging
'pairs' with their Labour counterparts under the system that allows matched
government and opposition MPs to escape many late-night votes.
Attending her first meeting of the parliamentary party, Ms Glenda Jackson,
newly installed in Hampstead and Highgate, showed none of the humility that
the Labour heirarchy expects of newcomers. To the chagrin of her 'seniors',
Ms Jackson arrived 10 minutes late and then calmly took a seat alongside the
party executive on the top table.
Her confidence was matched by the determination of some on the Conservative
side to make their first Commons television appearance during the election
of the Speaker.
Many ministers were forced to stand in the packed chamber, but Mr Gyles
Brandreth - who has swapped a career in light entertainment for the
constituency of Chester - managed somehow to find a place just behind the
prime minister.
In all, about a fifth of the 651 MPs who arrived to elect the Speaker of the
new House of Commons yesterday were newcomers - with 120 of them split
evenly between the Conservative and Labour benches.
Labour's new entrants displayed little of the deep gloom that has engulfed
the party leadership since April 9.
The party may have lost the election but the presence of their new
parliamentary recruits was testimony that they were individually victors.
Those looking for clues as to who has a role in the machinations after Mr
Neil Kinnock's resignation needed to glance no further than Mr Peter
Mandelson, the former campaigns director now installed in Hartlepool.
But it is on the Conservative side that the immediate interest of colleagues
and the media will focus. For the next while, the game will be to pick
'winners' destined for ministerial office and, perhaps 20 years hence, for
Downing Street.
Among those already on the inside track are a clutch of former Whitehall
advisers. Mr David Willetts, once of Mrs Margaret Thatcher's policy unit and
more recently director of research at the centre for policy studies, has an
obvious head start. So too do Mrs Judith Chaplin (Mr John Major's political
adviser) and Mr David Lidington (an adviser to Mr Douglas Hurd).
Mr Charles Hendry (formerly at social security), Mr Peter Luff (an aide at
one time to Lord Young) and Mr Alan Duncan (whose Westminster house was the
base for Mr John Major's leadership campaign) are among other putative
stars. On the right of the party, Mr John Whittingdale's loyal service as an
aide to Mrs Thatcher will stand him in good stead.
For those who want to climb on to the first rung of the ministerial ladder,
obedience to the party line will count for as much if not more than
intelligence.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
