<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 92 / UK dominant in European PCs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK and Ireland continued to dominate European personal computer
manufacturing last year and are now responsible for three out of every five
PCs built in Europe, according to Dataquest, the market research group.
Total PC sales last year exceeded 8.3m, worth Dollars 28bn (Pounds 15.8bn).
In its latest report, Dataquest estimates that of 5.4m PCs made in Europe
last year 4.2m were built by companies which bought semiconductors from
overseas for European PC production, and that 57 per cent of this production
took place in the UK and Ireland.
Including 'screwdriver' assembly, the UK alone represents nearly two-thirds
of total European PC manufacturing, led by companies such as Acorn in
Cambridge, IBM in Greenock, Research Machines in Oxford and Victor in High
Wycombe.
Italy is the largest volume manufacturer after the UK and Ireland, closely
followed by France and Germany. In spite of declining margins both Olivetti
and Apple also show strong growth in local production. Other volume assembly
plants that are emerging include Compaq, Elonex and Goldstar in the UK and
Vobis in Germany.
Dataquest forecasts that between last year and 1995 European PC
manufacturing will grow in line with the end-user PC market at a compound
growth rate of more than 11 per cent.
Other trends which are identified in the report include the growing role
played by 'no-name' companies in the European industry which account for 25
per cent of all PC production in Europe - equivalent to IBM's production -
the continuing move towards more powerful PCs, shorter product life cycles
and a further blurring of the differences between high-end desktop PCs and
UNIX workstations.
Dataquest also predicts that software developments will fuel PC memory chip
demand.
Mr Mike Williams, a Dataquest semiconductor research analyst, said '1991 was
clearly a tough year for personal computer dealerships in Europe. However
semiconductor memory chip sales soared by 32.5 per cent compared with an
overall unit PC market growth of 12 per cent'.
This growth in memory chip sales reflects the move towards memory-hungry
software and aggressive marketing tactics by PC suppliers.
European PC Manufacturing and Semiconductor Demand. Dataquest Europe. Tel
(44) 895 835050. Pounds 6,000
</TEXT>
