<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 92 / Brel workers may block control bid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE 6,500 workers at Brel, the privatised UK rolling-stock maker, are
threatening to block attempts by Asea Brown Boveri to take control of the
loss-making company.
Union representatives say that members wish to retain the shares they were
given on privatisation, and would be prepared to increase their holdings if
the price was right.
The Swiss-Swedish company ABB owns 40 per cent of the shares and has agreed
to buy the 40 per cent stake held by Trafalgar House subject to clearance by
the European Commission.
Once clearance is given, ABB must bid for the remaining 20 per cent of
shares held by the Brel workers and management, at the share price paid to
Trafalgar House.
However, Mr John Darby, chairman of Brel, told shareholders at the Brel
annual meeting in Crewe on Saturday that he was recommending employees not
to sell at that price, which was based on a 'nominal' valuation.
Although the company had made a loss of Pounds 41.6m in 1991, new orders and
the recent restructuring of Brel had made him much more optimistic about the
company's future.
Since ABB has a policy of taking 100 per cent ownership of subsidiaries, a
higher offer is likely to be made for the shares held by employees and the
management team.
Mr John Heavey, secretary of the RMT union branch at the Derby carriage
works, said yesterday that employees at all Brel factories had told him that
they wished to retain their shares and even to buy more.
'We are not looking for a better price,' he said. 'Holding shares gives us a
say in the company, including the right to say our penn'orth at the annual
meeting.
'We are also opposed because we can see a brighter future in the company and
want a stake in it,' Mr Heavey added.
Each employee was given 43 of the Pounds 10 shares when Brel was privatised
in 1989. About 6 per cent of the shares are owned by past and present
employees, with another 14 per cent held by the management team.
</TEXT>
