<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 92 / Mercedes reports sales up 35%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SALES of Mercedes cars in the UK since the April 9 general election have
been running about 35 per cent higher than a year ago, indicating that
recovery might be under way in the deeply depressed new-car market.
Mr Hans Tauscher, managing director of Mercedes-Benz (UK), warned yesterday
that recovery might be put at risk if two Brussels reports on new-car
prices, due to be published tomorrow, generate fresh uncertainty among UK
buyers about whether they are being charged excessively high prices compared
with other European Community markets.
Mercedes' increase in post-election sales contrasts sharply with the period
between the start of April and the general election, when sales were 10 per
cent below the already severely depressed levels of the same period a year
ago.
Mr Tauscher acknowledged that the extent of the upturn would have been
exaggerated as a result of potential buyers holding back in early April
until the result of the general election was known.
Speaking to a meeting of the Fleet Street Motoring Group, Mr Tauscher said
that the upturn was still 'a very positive sign'. He added: 'We all detect a
change of mood.'
Mr Tauscher said he was 'appalled' at the prospect of fresh dissension,
likely to be caused by tomorrow's publication of the two Brussels reports.
One, specifically on car prices, was produced for Sir Leon Brittan, the
European Community's competition commissioner. It shows substantial
country-by-country price differentials of up to 40 per cent. The other, for
Mr Martin Bangemann, the industry commissioner, also deals in part with car
prices but disagrees with the Brittan report on the causes.
Mr Tauscher said he was dismayed that the EC competition report appeared to
disagree with a previous one from the Monopolies and Mergers Commission,
'which after 20 months of investigation concluded . . . that the industry
had generally been pricing within EC parameters'. Under those guidelines,
prices should not vary by more than 12 per cent between member states for
long periods, and 18 per cent for shorter periods.
In spite of the potential short-term market setbacks, Mr Tauscher said he
believed that under a Conservative government the UK would enjoy sufficient
economic growth for the 'quality' car market - cars of over 2 litres and
costing more than Pounds 15,000 - to increase from sales of 190,000 this
year to 270,000 by 1996.
</TEXT>
