<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 92 / AEU chief raises spectre of Clause 4
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ISSUE of the Labour party's largely symbolic commitment to public
ownership has been thrown into the current leadership debate by Mr Bill
Jordan, leader of the AEU engineering union.
He called yesterday for the scrapping of Clause 4 of the party's
constitution, which pledges the party to supporting 'common ownership of the
means of production, distribution and exchange'.
His call came as the TGWU general union decided not to ballot its 1m members
before deciding who to support in the leadership contest.
Britain's biggest union had appeared to shift in favour of holding a ballot,
but decided at the last moment to revert to its original plan of consulting
members through its 8,000 branches.
In the most radical contribution to date from a union leader to the debate
about Labour's future, Mr Jordan told his union conference in Eastbourne
that Labour must become a party for managers and wealth creators and added
his voice to those demanding a substantial withdrawal of union involvement
in the Labour party.
He cautiously welcomed the appointments of Mrs Gillian Shephard to the
Employment Department and Mr Michael Heseltine to the Trade and Industry
Department as signs that the new government might be seeking more consensus
in industry.
Mr Jordan believes that the formal abolition of what has long since, in
practice, been superseded, would improve Labour's image. 'Clause 4 has
outlived its usefulness now,' he said. 'Labour have said they have no desire
for the common ownership of the means of production, but we need an
unambiguous statement about what Labour's position is.'
He said: 'While membership of the party is so public-sector top-heavy,
people will continue to say they are mainly a public-sector pressure group -
the party must work to correct this constituency imbalance.'
</TEXT>
