<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 92 / Walesa looks to France for his presidential model
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BOBINSKI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WARSAW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Lech Walesa yesterday announced his intention of becoming a
Gaullist-style executive president and further undermined his prime
minister, Mr Jan Olszewski, by naming two other candidates as better suited
to haul Poland out of its deepening political crisis.
'Our present system isn't functioning,' he told a news conference, 'so I am
suggesting a French-style presidential system to improve the efficiency of
government.'
He named Mr Tadeusz Mazowiecki, leader of Poland's largest party and prime
minister of the first post-Communist government as the best man to get
Poland's fractured political parties working together. But he also singled
out Mr Andrzej Olechowski, the finance minister, as 'the best qualified
person if we want quick and resolute reform'.
Despite his public endorsement for the two men, however, he stopped short of
asking Mr Olszewski to resign his premiership, adding: 'I don't exclude this
possibility even though there is no such necessity today.'
Mr Olechowski, a former senior trade and central bank official, is already a
key member of Mr Olszewski's government. He recently secured cabinet support
for cuts in public spending needed to keep the budget deficit below 5 per
cent of GDP.
But the cuts, which were needed to gain International Monetary Fund support
for Poland's economic reforms, still have to be approved by parliament. On
Friday parliament delayed for two weeks a vote to nullify a court ruling
which called on the government to reinstate welfare and pension cuts made
last year.
Failure to achieve the required 75 per cent support to overturn the court
ruling would double the proposed budget deficit and risk rekindling
hyperinflation. Mr Olechowski has made clear he would resign if this
happened, which in turn would almost certainly cause the collapse of the
government.
The difficulty of forming a solidly based government capable of supporting
tough economic policies from a fractured elected parliament of 29 political
parties and the ambiguous role played by Mr Walesa have underlined the need
for constitutional reform.
Mr Walesa spoke yesterday of the need to follow democratic procedures. But
in a clear reference to the possibility that he might put himself at the
head of a populist movement to back his demands, the former leader of the
anti-communist Solidarity movement warned that he did not 'exclude being
forced to be a strong president backed by a large party if these
calculations with the presidential system don't work'.
</TEXT>
